        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>At Mercantile Library&#45;&#45;10<hi rend="sup">th</hi> St.<lb/> 
                Phil. Oct. 4. 1881.<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. S. Morais&#45;&#45;<lb/>
                Dear Sir&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>Last year I had<lb/> the pleasure of calling on you&#44;<lb/> and afterwards of receiving one<lb/> or two polite and kind notes.<lb/></p>
            <p>I desire to ask you how you<lb/> would translate&#44; in Hebrew&#44;<lb/> the <hi rend="underline">first</hi> word in this sentence&#58;<lb/></p>
            <p>&#34;Grape&#45;juice is not a pleasant<lb/> drink until it is fermented.&#34;<lb/></p>
            <p>Or&#8212;if one says to a child&#44; eating<lb/> grapes&#44;&#45;&#45;&#34;Don&#39;t get the <hi rend="underline">grape&#45;juice</hi><lb/> on your clothes&#44;&#34; what Heb. Word<lb/> for grape&#45;juice&#63;  What Hebrew<lb/> word would have been used in<lb/> the time of Isaiah&#63;<lb/></p>
            <p>The only answer which I have<lb/> had from any good scholar is<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  How does this accord<lb/> with your views&#63;  Would you<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>prefer anything else&#63;  Please<lb/> to favor me with your decision.<lb/></p>
            <p>I have wished that some<lb/> Heb. Scholar would write a truly<lb/> <hi rend="underline">thorough</hi> essay on the much discussed<lb/> word &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  I have read many<lb/> arts. about it in Magazines&#44; Dic&#44;<lb/>tionaries&#44; and Encyclopaedias&#45;&#45;<lb/> but I do not find these satisfac<lb/>tory to me.  I wish to know what<lb/> information can be derived from<lb/> the Talmud and other books of<lb/> later Hebrew.  I have never been<lb/> able to see&#44; with entire clearness&#44;<lb/> what occasion the Hebrews had<lb/> for such a word.  <hi rend="underline">For what</hi><lb/> <hi rend="underline">precise mental conception</hi> did<lb/> they employ the word&#63;<lb/></p>
            <p>I have been informed that<lb/> there is&#44; in the Talmud&#44; evidence<lb/> that the popular use differed<lb/> from the Biblical&#59; and that&#44;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>in popular use&#44; the word was<lb/> employed for fruits&#8212;as the fig.<lb/></p>
            <p>When Zechariah said &#34;Corn<lb/> shall strengthen the young men&#44;<lb/> and &#91;Hebrew&#93; the maids&#44;&#34; he felt<lb/> that this was <hi rend="underline">just the word</hi> to express<lb/> his idea.  Now what <hi rend="underline">was</hi> that<lb/> idea&#63;  For some reason he did<lb/> not feel impelled to say &#91;Hebrew&#93;.<lb/></p>
            <p>The &#34;<hi rend="underline">Biblioteca Sacra</hi>&#34; for<lb/> Jan. last&#44; contained an Article<lb/> which I read with much in<lb/>terest&#44; in which the Hebrew<lb/> terms for the products of the vine<lb/> were discussed with conside<lb/>rable ability.  But I desire to<lb/> know more about &#91;Hebrew&#93;.<lb/></p>
            <p>I am most respectfully<lb/>
                Yours&#44;<lb/>
                S. C. Brace.<lb/></p>
        </body>
